## 7. Computed vs Watch vs WatchEffect Decision Tree

| Need | Use | Why |
|------|-----|-----|
| Derive a new value from existing state | `computed()` | Auto-cached, lazy evaluation |
| Track specific source(s) and run side effects | `watch(source, cb)` | Explicit deps, access to oldValue |
| Auto-track all deps and run side effects | `watchEffect()` | Automatic dep collection, simple cases |
| Access DOM after updates | `watchPostEffect()` | Guarantees DOM is updated |

**Rules:**
- **FORBIDDEN**: Side effects inside `computed()` — no API calls, no console.log, no mutating other refs
- **FORBIDDEN**: Deep watching large objects without specifying `{ deep: false }` or a specific getter path
- **REQUIRED**: Use `computed()` instead of methods for derived display data — leverage caching

```ts
// CORRECT — computed for derived state
const fullName = computed(() => `${user.value.first} ${user.value.last}`)

// CORRECT — watch with specific path for side effects
watch(() => route.params.id, (newId) => { fetchUser(newId) })

// FORBIDDEN — side effect in computed
const data = computed(() => {
  console.log('recomputing') // ❌ side effect
  return items.value.filter(i => i.active)
})
```

